rComments: David is one of the most organized and tech savvy profs I have ever had. Other than that he's quite robotic and cares very little about his students. Students are graded on participation and the course material is quite dry.

Professor Hanssen is a very friendly and patient prof. His exams and assignments were straightforward, and his grading criteria. He also provides good feedback showing you what you got wrong and why. I highly recommend this prof.

Very patient and respectful prof. Never got frustrated with students for asking questions, makes it clear he wants his students to do well. Made a boring seeming subject very interesting, you can tell he enjoys teaching. Three group projects throughout the semester. Almost every class has mandatory participation on wooclap so go to the lectures.

He has such a clear voice when teaching, it's like watching a really good youtube tutorial video. The class itself is easy, but he goes over everything with a lot of patience so no one is left confused about anything. He even records the practical tutorials for you so you can view them when doing the assignments - a wiki page, MS Excel,& MS Access.
Took this class in the first year. He is definitely a good professor. His exams and assignments were fair. Looking forward to taking more classes.

I really like that he is continuously trying to become a better prof; he was very open to students' comments about the course and his teaching. You will "excel" at the assignments if you just put in the work. The tests are a little tricky, but at least they were open book. Online learning :)

Professor Hanssen is nice and his class is straightforward. You will do well as long as you take textbook and lecture notes and do the assignments correctly. He provides tutorials for all the assignments so you know how to do everything. I didn't like that the midterm and final were on TopHat and could have been on Brightspace instead.
Expectations and guidelines for memos were not clear, and he tries to make the class difficult despite the common sense nature of the course.
